## Phase 4: The Relentless Loop

You enter a loop. Each cycle is one **iteration**. There is no
per-iteration time cap. There is no upper iteration count unless the
user passed `--max-iterations`. You stop only when Phase 5 (Milan
Check) clears.

### 4a. Iteration anatomy

Each iteration is:

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│  4a-i.    HEADER — print ITERATION N loud, prev Q TOTAL, target │
│  4a-ii.   PLAN — write iter-NN-plan.md (what / how / why /      │
│           alternatives / best practices / what can go wrong)    │
│  4a-iii.  SELF-REVIEW — append ## Self-review section, gate     │
│           plan-reviewed; END with ## Final decision: PROCEED    │
│  4a-iv.   BUILD — implement the slice the reviewed plan covers  │
│  4a-v.    COMMIT — atomic, conventional message                 │
│  4a-vi.   MERGE — rebase / resolve conflicts                    │
│  4a-vii.  DEPLOY — push to LIVE; verify with `gate deploy`      │
│  4a-viii. EVALUATE — run EVERY B/E/F observable AND score every │
│           Q-criterion 0–100 by judgment looking at live output  │
│  4a-ix.   REVIEW-AGENT triage — bot/CI comments                 │
│  4a-x.    JUDGE — set next iteration's goal                     │
│  4a-xi.   WRITE iter-NN.md — full template; gate phase + banned │
│  4a-xii.  PER-ITERATION MILAN CHECK — fill the rows including   │
│           Mission alignment + Smart human comparison; save      │
│           milan-check-iter-NN.md, decide CONTINUE/PROCEED       │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

The Milan Check runs at the **end of every iteration**, not only at
exit. It is the gate that decides whether the loop continues or you
move to Phase 5 (final report). Most iterations early in the run will
trivially CONTINUE (binary floor not met, or Q still climbing, or
Mission alignment still <75); the exercise of filling the rows still
matters because it shapes the next iteration's goal.

### 4a-1. Iteration 1 is special

> **Iteration 1 must end with code DEPLOYED to live AND at least one
> B-observable PASSING on the live URL.**

This is the rule the prior failed session violated — it stopped at
"implementation done" without ever deploying. If you find yourself at
the end of iteration 1 without a passing B-observable on a live URL,
**iteration 1 is incomplete**. Keep iterating with the same iteration
number until both conditions are met.

The intent: prove the deploy path works END-TO-END before doing more
work. A vertical slice through the most uncertain part of the
architecture, even if half-baked, is the right iteration-1 build.

### 4a-i. Iteration header — print this LOUD

The user wants to see iteration numbers as you work. Print this block
before doing anything else in the iteration, with the values filled in
from the prior iter-NN.md. This is one of the few places verbose
output is warranted — if Milan reads the transcript in the morning,
the iteration boundaries should be unmissable.

```
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
ITERATION N — $(date -u +%Y-%m-%dT%H:%M:%SZ)
───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
 Q TOTAL prev iteration:    [X / N×100, e.g., 720 / 1200]
 Q moving avg (last 5):     [Y or "n/a if N<6"]
 Mission alignment (last):  [Z / 100]
 Goal this round:           [one line — what you're pushing on]
 Lowest Q-criterion targeted: [Q-id, current score, rubric step you
                              intend to climb to]
 Phase order:               PLAN → REVIEW → BUILD → DEPLOY → EVAL → JUDGE
═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
```

You also write the same block at the top of `iter-NN.md` so the
artifact is self-contained.

### 4a-ii. PLAN — write `iter-NN-plan.md` BEFORE touching code

Each iteration starts with a written plan. This is the change v3
adds: the prior version went straight from "next goal" to BUILD,
which let subtle DRY violations and coupling sneak in.

Write `iter-NN-plan.md` with these sections (the `plan-reviewed` gate
greps for these exact headers):

```markdown
## Targeted Q-criterion
Q-id (e.g., Q4). The single criterion this iteration is the bet
against. The `attempts-exhausted` gate reads this to confirm the
agent declared a target — without it, the iteration counts as
NOT_TARGETED and doesn't contribute to the plateau evidence.

## Current score
N/100 — what Q<id> scored at the end of iter-(N-1) (or your
baseline judgment for iter 1).

## Projected score after this iteration
N/100 — your bet. Be honest: a small, achievable bet is fine; an
ambitious bet is fine. What's not fine is unfalsifiable hand-waving
("hopefully a little better"). The bet must be a number. At eval
time, you compare actual vs projected and write IMPROVED |
NO_MOVEMENT | REGRESSED to iter-NN.md.

## What I want to improve
The lowest-scoring Q-criterion (or highest-leverage open
B/E/F observable). Be specific: "push Q4 (voice-match) from 45 → 65"
not "improve voice".

## In which way
The concrete approach. Name the files / functions / data flow you
expect to touch. One paragraph.

## Why this way
Reasoning. Why this approach beats the alternatives below.

## Alternatives considered
At least TWO alternatives, each with a one-line rejection reason.
"I considered X but rejected because Y." If you can't name two
alternatives, you haven't actually considered the design space —
go think harder.
- A) <alternative> — rejected because <reason>
- B) <alternative> — rejected because <reason>

## Best practices that apply
Named patterns, principles, or examples from the codebase. Not
generic platitudes. Examples:
- "Strangler fig — keep the existing classifier path until the new
  per-user model is proven on ≥3 iterations."
- "Use the existing tone-classifier in tests/fixtures/tone.py;
  don't duplicate the tokenizer."
- "Brooks: this is essential complexity (per-user signal is real),
  not accidental — the LLM round-trip is unavoidable."

## Functions / methods to add or modify
v7-required: ≥1 entry. Each line names a path with extension and
the function/method affected, plus ADD or MODIFY plus a one-line
purpose. The `plan-substantive` gate parses these lines.
- <file/path.ext>:<function_name>: ADD — <one-line purpose>
- <file/path.ext>:<function_name>: MODIFY — <one-line purpose>

## Edge cases this slice must handle
v7-required: ≥3 enumerated. Each is a concrete edge condition AND
how this slice handles it (or why it's out of scope and won't
break). Generic prompts to reach into:
- Empty / single-element / max-size input
- Concurrent invocation of the same code path
- Time / TZ boundaries (DST, midnight UTC)
- Failure-injection (third-party down, DB unreachable)
- Partial state from a prior failed run
- Trust-boundary input (unauthenticated, cross-tenant)
- Input the planner generates that the validator rejects
Examples (substitute for your slice):
- Empty user history (<3 prior emails): fall back to default style
- Inference timeout (>200ms): proceed with prior baseline; log warn
- Non-English body: skip classifier; use generic template

## What can go wrong
Walk the blast radius. For each item, name the impact AND the
mitigation.
- DRY: <duplication risk>; mitigation: <reuse <named symbol>>
- Coupling: <module-X reaching into module-Y>; mitigation: <DI hook>
- Race: <concurrent path>; mitigation: <ordering / lock / idempotency>
- Backward compat: <existing caller>; mitigation: <fallback / flag>
- Blast radius: <what else this touches>; mitigation: <bounded scope>
- State machine impact: <transitions affected>; mitigation: <test>
- Failure mode the plan doesn't address: <name it>

## Files I expect to touch
- <path>
- <path>
```

### 4a-iii. SELF-REVIEW — append `## Self-review` to the same file

Now, *non-interactively*, review your own plan as a senior eng manager
would. This is inspired by the gstack `plan-eng-review` skill but
shrunk and self-contained — no AskUserQuestion, no asking the user.
You read your own plan and challenge it.

Append a `## Self-review` section to `iter-NN-plan.md` covering each
of the headings below, then end with a `## Final decision:` line:

```markdown
## Self-review

### Architecture
- Does this slice respect existing module boundaries? Where does it
  reach across?
- Is the chosen approach "boring by default" or am I spending an
  innovation token?
- Could this be a smaller, reversible change (strangler fig, feature
  flag, parallel impl) instead of a structural rewrite?

### DRY check
v7-required: must contain either a `Searched: <pattern>` line
naming what you grepped, OR a path-with-extension reference.
"Looks clean" without evidence fails `plan-substantive`.
- Walk the codebase for existing functions / classes / patterns that
  do what this plan duplicates. State what you grepped (`Searched:
  def *Classifier across harness/`) and what you found (or didn't).
- Name reused symbols with their path:line (e.g.,
  `tests/fixtures/tone-classifier.py:42`).
- If genuinely nothing exists: state the search terms used, so a
  reviewer can verify.

### Coupling check
v7-required: must name an existing module path.
- Does this introduce a new dependency edge? Name the edge with
  paths (e.g., `harness/planner/run.py → harness/llm/voice_match.py`).
- Is the direction right (high-level depends on low-level)?
- Could it be inverted via DI / interface? If yes, name the hook
  point (`harness/planner/run.py:14`).

### Race / ordering
- Are there concurrent execution paths? Webhook + cron, two requests
  to same row, mid-flight migration? Name the worst case AND the
  defense (lock, idempotency key, ordering invariant).
- "No race: this code path is single-writer because <evidence>" — if
  claiming none, name why.

### State machine impact
- Are any state transitions added, removed, or constrained? If yes,
  list them as `<from> → <to>`. Is `validate_transition` wired?
- "No transitions affected: verified by grep `validate_transition`
  in plan, no matches" — if claiming none, name what was verified.

### Test coverage gap
v7-required: must name a test file path.
- What tests cover the new behaviour? Cite the test file path
  (`tests/integration/test_voice_match.py`).
- What tests SHOULD cover it that don't yet? Add them in this
  iteration's build, not after.

### Backward compatibility
v7-required: must name ≥1 existing caller OR state what was searched.
- What existing callers / fixtures / clients does this affect? Cite
  them with paths.
- "No existing callers: grepped `voice_match` across `harness/` and
  `tests/`, no matches" — if claiming none, name the search.

### Failure mode the plan didn't address
- Re-read 02c-eval-framework.md F-rows. Does this slice introduce a
  new F-row that should be added? If yes, add it now AND name it.

### Style-guide check
v7-added. The repo's dominant reviewer's convictions live in
`~/.leadbay/knowledge/wiki/style/<repo>.md` if the repo has been
distilled. If the file doesn't exist, run `/distill-style` first
(it mines PR review history) — for a long /relentless run, the
upfront cost is small relative to the run length.
- Read `wiki/style/<repo>.md` (or note "no style page exists,
  invoked /distill-style → result: <file or no PRs>").
- Cite ≥1 rule from it that applies to this slice (e.g., "must:
  no `var` in Kotlin — using `val` for the new field"), OR state
  "no rules from style-guide apply to this slice (checked: rules
  about <topic-1>, <topic-2>, neither relevant)".

### Mission-fit
- Does this slice move us toward the mission, or only toward a Q
  number? If only toward a number, why is the number a good proxy?

### Cross-criterion side effects
- Does pushing this Q-criterion up risk pushing another DOWN?
  (e.g., adding a confirmation step might raise "Trust signals" but
  lower "Effort vs outcome".) Name the trade-off explicitly.

## Final decision: PROCEED | REVISED | ABORT
- If PROCEED: build as planned.
- If REVISED: write a new "## In which way (revised)" + "## Why
  revised" sub-section above this line, then re-run plan-reviewed.
- If ABORT: this iteration's goal becomes "rewrite the plan".
  iter-NN.md will record the abort and next iteration starts fresh.
```

Then run the gate:

```bash
N=<iteration number>
NZ=$(printf '%02d' $N)
PLAN_FILE="$ART_DIR/iter-$NZ-plan.md"
"$_LB_BIN/lb-relentless-gate" phase "Plan iter $N" "$PLAN_FILE" 30 "## Self-review"
"$_LB_BIN/lb-relentless-gate" plan-reviewed "$PLAN_FILE"
"$_LB_BIN/lb-relentless-gate" plan-substantive "$PLAN_FILE"
"$_LB_BIN/lb-relentless-gate" banned "$PLAN_FILE"
```

If `PLAN_NOT_REVIEWED`: fix the plan file. **Do not skip to BUILD.**
The whole point of v3's plan-then-review step is that engineering
mistakes are catchable when you write them down before coding,
expensive when you find them mid-build, and demoralising when you
find them mid-Phase-5.

Two failure modes to specifically avoid:

- **The "skim plan-eng-review" failure** — writing a plan that is
  clearly going through the motions ("Alternative A: don't do it.
  Alternative B: do it but worse."). Real alternatives only. The
  rejection reason has to be substantive.
- **The "review my plan with the plan I wrote" failure** — the
  self-review section just restates the plan in a different voice.
  The self-review must add information the plan didn't have:
  named conflicts, named existing code to reuse, named risks the
  plan glossed over.

### 4a-iv. Build

Now you build the slice the reviewed plan covers — exactly that
slice, not a larger one. The plan has been challenged in 4a-iii;
trust the plan and execute it. If during BUILD you discover something
that invalidates the plan, STOP, re-open `iter-NN-plan.md`, add a
"## Mid-build revision" section, re-run `plan-reviewed`, then
continue.

Slice for max info-per-change. The shape of a typical relentless run
(assuming non-trivial feature):

- **Iteration 1:** vertical slice exercising the most uncertain part of
  the architecture end-to-end, even if half-baked. Find what's hard
  before committing to a direction. End with a deploy and ≥1 B-pass.
- **Iterations 2-8:** fill in happy-path observables (Dimension 1) and
  hit the binary floor: every B passes, no regressions.
- **Iterations 8-15:** harden against edges (E) and failure modes (F).
  Pick the highest-leverage open observable.
- **Iterations 15-60+:** quality polish — the bulk of the run. Each
  iteration picks the lowest-scoring Q-criterion and tries to push it
  up one rubric band. Some attempts will fail; that's expected and
  counts as the "exploration proof" the Milan Check demands.
  Saturation typically arrives in the 40–80 range.

Don't spread changes across 30 files in one iteration. Slice such that
each iteration is small enough to deploy, score, and learn from.

**Picking the next Q-target:** read `iter-(N-1).md`, find the
Q-criterion with the lowest score whose rubric you have a concrete
idea for moving. Set that as iteration N's goal in the iteration
header AND in `iter-NN-plan.md`'s "What I want to improve" section.
If multiple Q-criteria are tied at the bottom, pick the one whose
rubric step you have the clearest plan for.

### 4a-v. Commit

Atomic commits, conventional messages, one logical change each. Trailer
with co-author per repo convention. NO `git add -A` — stage by name to
avoid accidentally including secrets, fixtures, or unrelated edits.

### 4a-vi. Merge

```bash
git fetch origin
git rebase origin/<base-branch>  # or merge, per repo convention
```

**Conflict resolution is your job, not the user's.** Read both sides,
understand intent, resolve. If the other side's commit message says
"don't change X" or the conflicting code is clearly intentional and
recent, prefer their version and adapt your change around it. If you
made the conflicting change and it's still right, take yours. Do NOT
abort the rebase. Do NOT silently drop the other side's work. Verify
the merged tree builds before continuing.

If conflicts are genuinely beyond your judgment (e.g., a refactor in
progress that fundamentally rearranges your area), stash your work,
log a `DEFERRED` decision in the iteration log, and pivot to the next
highest-leverage observable that doesn't touch the contested area.

### 4a-vii. Deploy

Use the project's deploy mechanism. Do not invent your own. Verify it
went LIVE.

```bash
# Detect platform from Phase 1a, then run the corresponding command:
# fly deploy / vercel --prod / npm run deploy / git push origin main / etc.
git push origin <branch>   # if push-to-deploy
# OR
fly deploy --remote-only   # etc.

# Wait for the deploy to actually be live
SHA_SHORT="$(git rev-parse --short HEAD)"
"$_LB_BIN/lb-relentless-gate" deploy "https://<host>/health" "$SHA_SHORT"
```

If the deploy gate fails: the iteration is INCOMPLETE. Treat the failure as
the iteration's outcome, log it, next iteration's goal is "fix the
deploy". Do not proceed to evaluation against an undeployed change.

**Production guardrails before deploying to prod:**

- `git log origin/main..HEAD` — anything in there that looks scary?
- The diff doesn't touch shared infra or other features unintentionally
- Migrations have been verified on a copy of prod-shape data
- A rollback path exists (revert commit + re-deploy is usually enough)

If any guardrail fails, deploy to staging and note it.

**Live-users protection:** if Phase 1c said "yes, there are live users"
and your iteration touches a code path users hit (auth, payment, data
mutation), deploy to staging instead of prod. The prod-only proof goes
in the morning report.

### 4a-viii. Evaluate

Run EVERY observable from EVERY dimension. Not just new ones — ALL.
You may have introduced a regression in B3 while fixing E7. Re-running
the full suite catches that.

There are TWO distinct kinds of evaluation in this phase:

**(1) Binary B/E/F evaluation — deterministic.** Use the right tool
per observable:

- **UI** → `$B` (browse), screenshots saved to
  `$ART_DIR/iter-$N-evidence/B1.png` (etc.)
- **API** → `curl` against the live deployed endpoint, save response
  to `$ART_DIR/iter-$N-evidence/B2.json`
- **DB** → read-only psql / supabase queries against the actual
  production (or staging) DB
- **Side-effect** → check the actual destination (S3 bucket, email
  sandbox, webhook log, queue depth, error tracker)

PASS / FAIL / DEFERRED with named evidence per row.

**(2) Q evaluation — judgment, not metrics.** This is the part that
makes /relentless work for LLM-driven systems. For each Q-criterion
in `02b-criteria.md`:

- Trigger the live behaviour the criterion measures. Save evidence
  (screenshot, log, generated artefact, transcript) under
  `$ART_DIR/iter-$N-evidence/Q<id>-...`.
- LOOK at the evidence and THINK like a brilliant human reviewer.
  Score against the 0–100 rubric you wrote in 2b. The score should
  reflect what a thoughtful person would actually say, not what fits
  the rubric mechanically.
- In the "Notes" column, write what specifically would push the
  score higher. This is the seed for the next iteration's plan.
- If you find yourself scoring everything 70–80, you're either
  short-cutting the rubric or the rubric was written too generously.
  Re-read 2b and rescore honestly. The whole gradient-descent only
  works if scores are honest.

Two anti-shortcut rules:

- **No batch-scoring.** Score one criterion at a time, with the
  evidence in front of you. Don't write "Q1=72, Q2=70, Q3=68" from
  memory after running tests.
- **No symmetric movement.** It is suspicious if every Q score moved
  +5 in one iteration. That usually means you scored optimistically
  rather than judgmentally. A real iteration moves 1–3 criteria
  meaningfully and leaves the rest near unchanged.

**No skip markers.** If your test framework supports skip markers
(pytest `@pytest.mark.skip`, jest `xtest`, RSpec `xit`, etc.) and you
encounter a missing-env condition that would normally trigger one,
DO NOT use the skip marker. Instead:

- The iteration's goal becomes "set up the env so this test runs."
- OR mark the observable `DEFERRED` with a *specific named blocker* and
  a *specific plan to unblock* in the next iteration.

A test suite output of "32 passed, 7 skipped" without each skip
itemised in the eval table is a violation of Iron Law #2.

Output the eval table to `iter-NN.md`. Binary rows (B/E/F) are
PASS/FAIL/DEFERRED. Q rows are scored 0–100 with the delta vs the
prior iteration:

```markdown
## Eval — Iteration N

### Binary observables (B / E / F)

| Dim | ID  | Observable                       | Result    | Evidence |
|-----|-----|----------------------------------|-----------|----------|
| B   | B1  | ...                              | PASS      | iter-N-evidence/B1.png |
| B   | B2  | ...                              | FAIL      | iter-N-evidence/B2.log |
| E   | E1  | ...                              | DEFERRED  | reason: STRIPE_KEY missing per Phase 1c-B; unblock: get key |
| F   | F1  | ...                              | PASS      | log line at request_id=... |

Binary: PASS K/N · FAIL J/N · DEFERRED D/N (each with named blocker)

### Quality scores (Q) — 0–100 against the Phase 2b rubrics — JUDGMENT, not metrics

| ID  | Criterion           | Score (iter N) | Δ vs N-1 | Evidence | Notes — what a brilliant human would push to next |
|-----|---------------------|----------------|----------|----------|----------------------------------------------------|
| Q1  | Knows the user      | 62             | +7       | iter-N-evidence/Q1-suggest.png | next: pick up that the user disabled Friday meetings on iter 3 |
| Q2  | Voice & tone match  | 45             | +0       | iter-N-evidence/Q2-email.txt   | next: drop the corporate "I hope this finds you well" opener |
| Q3  | Fault-tolerance     | 78             | +3       | iter-N-evidence/Q3-net-down.log | next: surface the retry to the user instead of silent |
| ... | ...                 | ...            | ...      | ...      | ...                                                 |

Q TOTAL (sum of scores): SUM_N (Δ vs N-1: ±X)
Q AVG: AVG_N
Q MOVING_AVG (last 5 iters incl. this): MA_N
```

Saving the score history matters: the Milan Check reads the last 5
iterations' Q TOTAL to detect saturation. Always include the row even
on iterations where Q didn't change ("Δ 0" is data — it shows the
attempt didn't move the score, which is the "exploration proof" the
Milan Check looks for).

The `Q TOTAL (sum of scores): SUM_N` line is required — the
`q-saturated` gate parses it. With ≥12 criteria × 0–100, Q TOTAL is
in the 0–1200+ range; saturation default range is 12 across a window
of 5 iterations.

For every FAIL: capture which observable, actual result, your one-line
diagnosis hypothesis, and what the next iteration will try.

### 4a-ix. Review-agent triage

If the repo has automated reviewers (CodeRabbit, Codex review, Claude
review action, ESLint comments on PR, etc.), pull comments and triage:

```bash
gh pr view --json comments --jq '.comments[] | {author: .author.login, body: .body}' 2>/dev/null
gh api repos/:owner/:repo/pulls/<num>/comments --jq '.[] | {path, line, body, author: .user.login}' 2>/dev/null
```

For each comment:

- **Bug / correctness flag:** address it. Add a temporary observable
  (`Fx-N`) so the next iteration verifies the fix.
- **Style / preference:** if it's quick and clearly right, do it. If
  taste-only, log a DECISION explaining why you chose your version and
  move on.
- **Architecture concern:** weigh against your Phase 2 framework. If
  it surfaces a missed failure mode, add it to Dimension 4 and treat
  it as a real observable.

Do not get stuck in a comment-resolution death spiral. The framework
is your north star, not the bot's preferences.

### 4a-x. Judge — decide the next move

Look at the eval result and ask, with high-thinking judgment:

1. **Highest-leverage thing next?** Usually "the failing observable
   whose fix unlocks the most others." Sometimes "rip out the
   architecture I chose in iteration 1 and try the alternative I
   rejected." Have the discipline to pivot if evidence warrants it.

2. **What did I learn this iteration that wasn't on the framework?**
   New observable? Add it. New failure mode? Add it. New quality bar
   surfaced by something I noticed? Add it. The framework grows.

3. **Anything getting worse?** Regressions are the canary that the
   architecture isn't sound. Two regressions in a row → step back, log
   a DECISION, possibly pivot.

4. **Could this be done better?** Phase 5 will demand an answer.
   Pre-empt now. If "better" is achievable in the next iteration,
   that's the next iteration's goal.

Set the next iteration's goal explicitly. One line.

